<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
     THEORY 1 — PROBABILITY FUNDAMENTALS
     ═══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="theory">Probability Fundamentals</h2>

<p>A <strong>sample space</strong> Ω is the complete set of all possible outcomes of an experiment. An <strong>event</strong> A is any subset of Ω. For experiments with equally-likely outcomes:</p>

<div class="gd-formula-panel">
  <div class="gd-formula-label">Classical Definition</div>
  <div class="gd-formula">$$P(A) = \frac&#123;|A|&#125;&#123;|\Omega|&#125; = \frac&#123;\text&#123;number of favourable outcomes&#125;&#125;&#123;\text&#123;total outcomes&#125;&#125;, \quad 0 \le P(A) \le 1$$</div>
</div>

<h3 id="axioms">Kolmogorov Axioms</h3>

<p>All probability theory rests on three axioms. Axiom 3 is the key one — it forces us to subtract the overlap in the addition rule.</p>

<ol style="color:var(--gd-text-1);font-size:16px;padding-left:22px;line-height:2;">
  <li>$P(A) \ge 0$ for every event $A$</li>
  <li>$P(\Omega) = 1$ — the sample space is certain</li>
  <li>If $A \cap B = \emptyset$ (mutually exclusive), then $P(A \cup B) = P(A) + P(B)$</li>
</ol>

<h3 id="rules">Derived Rules</h3>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Complement</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$P(A^c) = 1 - P(A)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Use when "at least one" or "not" appears — complement is usually shorter.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Impossibility</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$P(\emptyset) = 0$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Empty event (impossible outcome) has zero probability.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-formula-panel">
  <div class="gd-formula-label">General Addition Rule</div>
  <div class="gd-formula">$$P(A \cup B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A \cap B)$$</div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--insight">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">Why subtract P(A∩B)?</span>
    Outcomes in A∩B get counted once in P(A) and again in P(B). Subtracting once restores the correct count. The Venn diagram below makes this geometric.
  </div>
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">Mutually exclusive ≠ independent</span>
    Mutually exclusive (A∩B = ∅) means they can't both happen. Independent means knowing A happened doesn't change P(B). These are different properties — don't confuse them.
  </div>
</div>


