<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
     THEORY 2 — COUNTING PRINCIPLES
     ═══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="counting">Counting Principles</h2>

<p><strong>Multiplication principle:</strong> if a task has two independent steps — step 1 in $m$ ways and step 2 in $n$ ways — the total number of outcomes is $m \times n$. This extends to any number of steps.</p>

<p style="color:var(--gd-text-2);font-size:15px;margin-bottom:20px;">Example: toss a coin (2 outcomes) then roll a die (6 outcomes) → 12 equally-likely outcomes.</p>

<h3 id="perm">Permutations — order matters</h3>

<p>Choose $r$ items from $n$ <em>in a specific order</em>. Each different ordering is a distinct permutation.</p>

<div class="gd-formula-panel">
  <div class="gd-formula-label">Permutation formula</div>
  <div class="gd-formula">$$P(n,r) = \frac&#123;n!&#125;&#123;(n-r)!&#125; = n \times (n-1) \times \cdots \times (n-r+1)$$</div>
</div>

<p style="color:var(--gd-text-1);font-size:15px;">Think of it as filling $r$ slots: $n$ choices for slot 1, $(n-1)$ for slot 2, ..., $(n-r+1)$ for slot $r$.</p>

<h3 id="comb">Combinations — order doesn't matter</h3>

<p>Choose $r$ items from $n$ where the <em>set</em> chosen is what counts, not the sequence.</p>

<div class="gd-formula-panel">
  <div class="gd-formula-label">Combination formula</div>
  <div class="gd-formula">$$C(n,r) = \binom&#123;n&#125;&#123;r&#125; = \frac&#123;n!&#125;&#123;r! \cdot (n-r)!&#125; = \frac&#123;P(n,r)&#125;&#123;r!&#125;$$</div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--insight">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">Why divide by r! ?</span>
    Every set of $r$ items can be arranged in $r!$ different orders. All those $r!$ permutations represent the same combination. So $C(n,r) = P(n,r) \div r!$. The interactive below shows this ratio live.
  </div>
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">Keyword cues in GATE problems</span>
    "Arrange", "rank", "schedule", "order" → permutation. "Select", "choose", "committee", "group", "team" → combination.
  </div>
</div>

<p style="color:var(--gd-text-1);font-size:15px;margin-bottom:4px;"><strong style="color:var(--gd-text-0);">Useful identities:</strong></p>
<ul style="color:var(--gd-text-1);font-size:15px;padding-left:20px;line-height:2.1;">
  <li>$C(n,0) = C(n,n) = 1$</li>
  <li>$C(n,1) = n$</li>
  <li>$C(n,r) = C(n, n-r)$ — choosing $r$ to include = choosing $n-r$ to exclude</li>
  <li>$C(n,r) + C(n,r+1) = C(n+1, r+1)$ — Pascal's identity</li>
</ul>


