<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
     WORKED EXAMPLES
     ═══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="examples">Worked Examples</h2>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 1 · Without replacement</span>
    <p>A bag contains 5 red and 3 blue balls. Two balls are drawn without replacement. Find the probability that both are red.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong style="color:var(--gd-text-0);">Method A — Multiplication rule:</strong></p>
    <p>P(1st red) = 5/8. Given 1st is red, 4 red remain from 7 total.</p>
    <p>P(2nd red | 1st red) = 4/7</p>
    <p>P(both red) = 5/8 × 4/7 = 20/56</p>
    <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong style="color:var(--gd-text-0);">Method B — Combinations:</strong></p>
    <p>Ways to choose 2 red from 5 = $C(5,2) = 10$. Total ways to choose 2 from 8 = $C(8,2) = 28$.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">P(both red) = C(5,2) / C(8,2) = 10/28 = 5/14 ≈ 0.357</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 2 · Permutation</span>
    <p>From 8 athletes, how many ways can gold, silver, and bronze medals be awarded?</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p>Order matters (gold ≠ silver ≠ bronze) → permutation.</p>
    <p>P(8,3) = 8 × 7 × 6 = 8! / 5!</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">P(8,3) = 336 ways</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 3 · Complement trick</span>
    <p>A committee of 3 is chosen from 4 men and 3 women. Find the probability the committee has at least one woman.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p>Direct count is messy (1 woman, 2 women, 3 women — three cases). Use complement:</p>
    <p>P(at least 1 woman) = 1 − P(no women) = 1 − P(all men)</p>
    <p>Total ways = $C(7,3) = 35$. All-men ways = $C(4,3) = 4$.</p>
    <p>P(all men) = 4/35</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">P(at least 1 woman) = 1 − 4/35 = 31/35 ≈ 0.886</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 4 · Inclusion-Exclusion (3 events)</span>
    <p>In a class of 60, 30 study Maths (M), 25 study Stats (S), 20 study CS (C). Overlaps: M∩S = 10, M∩C = 8, S∩C = 7, M∩S∩C = 4. How many study at least one?</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p>|M∪S∪C| = |M| + |S| + |C| − |M∩S| − |M∩C| − |S∩C| + |M∩S∩C|</p>
    <p>= 30 + 25 + 20 − 10 − 8 − 7 + 4</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">= 54 students study at least one subject</div>
  </div>
</div>


<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
     GATE ANGLE
     ═══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="gd-gate-box">
  <div class="gd-gate-box__title">GATE DA Angle</div>
  <p><strong>Complement shortcut:</strong> "at least one" / "at least k" problems — always try 1 − P(none) first. Saves a multi-case sum.</p>
  <p><strong>Keyword trap:</strong> "arrange" / "rank" / "seat" → permutation. "Select" / "choose" / "committee" / "sample" → combination.</p>
  <p><strong>3-event inclusion-exclusion:</strong> P(A∪B∪C) = P(A)+P(B)+P(C) − P(A∩B) − P(A∩C) − P(B∩C) + P(A∩B∩C). Memorise the sign pattern: +singles −pairs +triple.</p>
  <p><strong>Without vs with replacement:</strong> Without replacement → denominator shrinks each draw, use combinations. With replacement → draws are independent, multiply probabilities directly.</p>
</div>

<div class="gd-page-nav">
